{
  "updated_summary": "In a modern, well-lit kitchen with a marble countertop and city views, a muscular, shirtless man in red athletic shorts and a watch demonstrates the MyFitnessPal nutrition tracking app on his smartphone. He explains the app's flexibility, noting one can "delete all the stuff from oats" to "change it" from their routine, and emphasizes that the app is "not free anymore" but urges viewers to "invest in your health." After a distinct scanning sound, he scans a bag of 'Organic Wave Rolled Oat', and the app displays its nutritional values: \"100 grams of oats is 370 calories, 55 carb, 8 fats, 14 protein.\" He then states his intention to add protein, mentioning his decade of experience and "database of over a thousand recipes." He scans a black 'ISOPEPT' container, which the app identifies as 'Isopept Hydrolyzed Whey Protein Isolate, Peanut Butter Cups' with 130 calories. He notes the oats provide 14 grams of protein and one scoop of protein is 27 grams, deciding to add \"two scoops\" and humorously remarking, \"Living dangerously,\" while pointing to his chest and abdomen to show the app already displays \"68 grams of protein in my meal,\" which he finds \"awesome.\" Next, he scans a blue and white 'Oatly' oat milk carton, identified by the app as 'Low Fat High Calcium Milk' with 109 calories per 250ml, describing it as "low fat" and advising viewers to choose "calorie friendly" options like "oat milk" or "almond milk." With a distinct tap sound, he adjusts the serving size from 250ml to "about 350 mils," declaring, \"And voila. Meal one done,\" confirming, \"that's my protein oats, right? So that's breakfast done.\" The app interface on his smartphone shows his daily calorie and macro goals. He concludes by reading his remaining nutrients from the app: \"119 carbs left, 36 fat, 123 protein,\" while continuing to gesture expressively. The kitchen features dark glass display cabinets, warm under-cabinet lighting, and a decorative vase visible in the glass cabinet."
}
